item.title: DarkRSC New Server
item.dc:creator: @hornyhamster hornyhamster
item.description:
@hornyhamster wrote:

Noone who is truely interested in trying RSC will play one server, and decides it sucks.

In reality, they will try out 3-4 less populated servers and the popular servers like RSCA and RSCE, then find one they really like and stick with it, or return to whatever they were playing to begin with.

I would personally prefer that new server coders would privately host and have friends test the server for bugs, then host a free to play version of the game publicly. Only when they have created features worth paying for should the game accept subscriptions.

But if someone is trying to create a server you should support them, offer advise and constructive criticism rather than ranting about how wrong it is and how they are responsible for all of rsc’s problems. You have to remember that many of the server’s you’ve played and loved started out crappy… in some form or another. New developers are what keeps RSC alive, not what kills it.

Read full topic

item.title: DarkRSC New Server
item.dc:creator: @hornyhamster hornyhamster
item.description:
@hornyhamster wrote:

People need to stop ranting.

He is obviously new to the whole rsc p server creating thing, hes trying to learn, trying to make a good server, and a bunch of uptight dicks jump up and down and say its crap, rsce is better, its gonna die.

New coders and people who try to make servers are what keep p servers alive. Mistakes and failing is what makes people learn.

I played RSCE from the first day it was hosted, we all know its a successful server, but its not for everyone, you can’t crap on someone’s work cause it doesn’t meet your satisfaction.

If you want tips on mapmaking, feel free to message me, I’ll give you some pointers.

I’m sure if you keep at it, and learn as you go, you’ll get a nice server working in no time.

Goodluck
